description:
Backend exposes real-time queue metrics:

GET /api/system/telemetry
{
  queues: {
    detection_queue: int,  // Pending detections
    analysis_queue: int    // Pending analyses
  },
  latencies: {
    watch: {p50, p95, p99, avg_ms},
    detect: {p50, p95, p99, avg_ms},
    batch: {p50, p95, p99, avg_ms},
    analyze: {p50, p95, p99, avg_ms}
  }
}

WebSocket /ws/system also broadcasts queue depths every 5 seconds.

**UI Features:**
1. Queue depth badges showing pending items
2. Warning indicator when queues are backing up (>10 items)
3. Optional: Processing pipeline diagram with current counts
4. Optional: Latency percentile display for debugging

This helps operators see if the system is keeping up with camera uploads or falling behind.

The DLQ endpoints (/api/dlq/requeue/{queue_name}, /api/dlq/requeue-all/{queue_name}, DELETE /api/dlq/{queue_name}) allow destructive operations (requeuing and deleting jobs) without any authentication. In a multi-user or network-accessible deployment, this could allow unauthorized users to manipulate the job queues.

Affected endpoints:
- POST /api/dlq/requeue/{queue_name}
- POST /api/dlq/requeue-all/{queue_name}  
- DELETE /api/dlq/{queue_name}

Recommendation: Add API key or token-based authentication for admin-level endpoints.

Create a React hook to listen for service_status WebSocket events.

## File to create
- `frontend/src/hooks/useServiceStatus.ts`

## Hook Interface
```typescript
interface ServiceStatus {
  service: 'redis' | 'rtdetr' | 'nemotron';
  status: 'healthy' | 'unhealthy' | 'restarting' | 'restart_failed' | 'failed';
  message?: string;
  timestamp: string;
}

function useServiceStatus(): {
  services: Record<string, ServiceStatus>;
  hasUnhealthy: boolean;
}
```

## Behavior
- Subscribe to WebSocket on mount
- Filter for type: "service_status" messages
- Maintain map of latest status per service
- Compute hasUnhealthy flag for quick checks

## Acceptance Criteria
- Hook subscribes to existing WebSocket connection
- Status updates trigger re-renders
- Handles reconnection gracefully

When backend container is restarted, nginx caches the old IP address causing 502 Bad Gateway errors with 'Host is unreachable'.

Solution: Add resolver directive to nginx.conf to use Docker's internal DNS with short TTL:

```nginx
resolver 127.0.0.11 valid=10s;
set $backend_upstream backend:8000;
proxy_pass http://$backend_upstream;
```

This forces nginx to re-resolve DNS on each request or at short intervals.

Files: frontend/nginx.conf
